Objective
Build a fully functional web application that allows non-technical users to generate interactive data dashboards from natural language queries. The system must interpret a user's plain-English request, query a dataset, select appropriate visualizations, and render a cohesive, interactive dashboard in real time.

Background & Context
Refer to the provided problem statement (see PDF). The solution should empower business executives to ask questions like *"Show me monthly sales revenue for Q3 broken down by region and highlight the top-performing product category"* and instantly receive a dashboard with relevant charts.

Detailed Requirements
Functional Requirements

1.Natural Language Input

A text box where users can type queries in plain English.

Support for progressively complex queries (e.g., simple aggregation, filters, grouping, time series, comparisons).

2.LLM-Powered Query Translation

Integrate Google Gemini API to convert natural language into a structured query (e.g., SQL for a database, or pandas operations for a CSV).

Use clever prompt engineering to ensure accurate SQL generation, chart type selection, and handling of ambiguous requests.

3.Data Source

Initially, use a hardcoded sample dataset (e.g., a CSV file or SQLite database) containing sales data with fields like date, region, product_category, revenue, units_sold, etc.

Bonus: Allow users to upload their own CSV file and query it interactively (Data Format Agnostic).

4.Chart Generation & Visualization

Automatically choose the most appropriate chart type based on the query and data shape:

Line chart for time series

Bar chart for categorical comparisons

Pie/donut chart for parts of a whole

Scatter plot for correlations

Tables for detailed breakdowns

Use a modern charting library (e.g., Recharts, Chart.js, Plotly) to render interactive charts with tooltips, zoom, and hover effects.

5.Dashboard Layout

Display multiple charts and insights in a clean, responsive grid layout.

Include a title and brief description of what the dashboard shows.

Show the generated SQL or query for transparency (optional but nice).

6.Error Handling & Ambiguity

Gracefully handle vague or impossible queries (e.g., "show me everything"): ask for clarification or return a helpful message.

Prevent hallucination: if the data cannot answer the query, the system should clearly state that instead of fabricating numbers.

7.User Experience

Clean, modern, and intuitive UI.

Loading indicators while the dashboard is being generated.

Ability to interact with charts (hover, zoom, filter if possible).

Bonus: Follow-up questions / chat with the dashboard to refine the view (e.g., "now filter to East Coast only").

Try To create a Parallax Effect Motion to make it look attractive and create 3d elements to enhance the visuals, but don't mess it up.

8.Backend API

Expose endpoints for:

Receiving a natural language query and returning chart configurations + data.

(If CSV upload) handling file uploads and querying the uploaded data.

Use FastAPI (Python) or Node.js/Express for the backend.

Data Storage

Use SQLite or PostgreSQL for persistent storage, or simply work with in‑memory data frames for CSV uploads.

Non‑Functional Requirements
Performance: Dashboard should generate in < 5 seconds for typical queries.

Scalability: Code should be modular and well‑structured for future extensions.

Security: If using API keys, store them in environment variables; never expose them client‑side.

Recommended Tech Stack (Strictly Follow)
Layer	Technologies
Frontend	React (with Vite or Next.js) – for rich interactivity and aesthetics.
Charting	Recharts (preferred) or Plotly – both support tooltips and zoom.
Backend	Python + FastAPI – easy integration with Gemini and data processing.
LLM	Google Gemini API (via google.generativeai Python package).
Database	SQLite (for simplicity) plus support for CSV uploads (pandas).
Styling	Tailwind CSS or Material‑UI for a polished, modern look.
Deployment	Provide clear instructions to run locally (e.g., docker-compose or manual setup).
Note: If you prefer a rapid‑prototyping framework like Streamlit to speed up development, you may use it, but ensure the final result meets the aesthetics & UX criteria (clean design, interactivity). However, React is strongly recommended for better chart interactivity and customisation.

Evaluation Criteria to Keep in Mind
Your implementation will be judged on:

Accuracy (40%)

Correct data retrieval (SQL/query generation)

Appropriate chart selection

Robust error handling

Aesthetics & UX (30%)

Visual design (clean, modern)

Interactivity (tooltips, hover, zoom)

Intuitive user flow with loading states

Approach & Innovation (30%)

Robust architecture from text → LLM → database → frontend

Effective prompt engineering and hallucination prevention

Use of clever techniques (RAG, agentic workflows) if applicable

Bonus Points

Follow‑up questions / chat with dashboard (+10)

Upload your own CSV and query it (+20)

